Atlanta Falcons quarterback Michael Vick pled not guilty to conspiracy involving competitive dogfighting, procuring and training dogs for fighting, and conducting the enterprise across state lines.
He was released without bond.
Investigators found dogs and Bad Newz Kennels dogfighting equipment on Vick’s property in Surry County, Virginia.
A Federal grand jury indicted Vick, Tony Taylor, Purnell Peace, and Quanis Phillips.
All face six years in prison, $350,000 in fines, and restitution.
Vick is barred from training camp while the NFL investigates.
Sponsors dropped endorsements.
Animal rights groups protested.
Taylor pled guilty before Judge Henry Hudson and corroborated charges against others.
